Yes, you can definitely use Latex to create tables. In fact, Latex has many features and packages specifically designed for creating high-quality tables with ease. One such package is `tabularx`, which allows you to create tables with adjustable column widths. Here's an example code for a simple table:
```
documentclass{article}
begin{document}

Here's a simple table:

begin{center}
begin{tabular}{|c|c|}
hline
Column 1 & Column 2
hline
Row 1, Column 1 & Row 1, Column 2
Row 2, Column 1 & Row 2, Column 2
hline
end{tabular}
end{center}

end{document}
```

This will create a table with two columns and two rows, each containing some simple text. The `|c|c|` argument in the `tabular` environment specifies that there should be two centered columns in the table with vertical lines separating them. We also use the `hline` command to draw horizontal lines above and below the table headers and between the rows.

Yes, you can add color to your tables in Latex using the `colortbl` package. Here's an example code for a table with colored rows:
```
documentclass{article}
usepackage[table]{xcolor}
begin{document}

Here's a table with colored rows:

begin{center}
begin{tabular}{|c|c|}
hline
rowcolor{gray!50} Column 1 & Column 2
hline
Row 1, Column 1 & Row 1, Column 2
rowcolor{gray!25} Row 2, Column 1 & Row 2, Column 2
hline
end{tabular}
end{center}

end{document}
```

In this example, we use the `xcolor` package and the `table` option to define colors for our table rows using the `rowcolor` command. The argument `gray!50` specifies that the row should be filled with a shade of gray that is 50% dark, while `gray!25` specifies a shade that is 25% dark.

Including images in Latex is also possible by using the `graphicx` package. Here's an example code for including an image in a Latex document:
```
documentclass{article}
usepackage{graphicx}
begin{document}

Here's an example image:

begin{figure}[h]
centering
includegraphics[width=0.5textwidth]{example-image-a}
caption{This is an example caption for the image.}
label{fig:example}
end{figure}

end{document}
```

In this code, we use the `includegraphics` command to include an image in our document. The argument `width=0.5textwidth` specifies that the image should take up half of the text width, while the `figure` environment provides a way to add a caption and label to the image using the `caption` and `label` commands respectively. The label can be used later in the document to reference the image using the `ref` command.

