To generate all possible permutations of words in the given list "world," "amazing," and "the" to form meaningful sentences, we can use a recursive approach. We can start by creating an empty string and then recursively add each word to the string until all words have been used. We can then add the formed sentence to a list of sentences and continue with the next permutation until all permutations have been generated.
Here's an example code snippet in PHP:
```
php
$words = array("world", "amazing", "the");
$sentences = array();
function generateSentences($prefix, $remainingWords) {
global $sentences;
if (count($remainingWords) == 0) {
$sentences[] = $prefix;
} else {
for ($i = 0; $i < count($remainingWords); $i++) {
$newPrefix = $prefix . " " . $remainingWords[$i];
$newRemainingWords = array_merge(array_slice($remainingWords, 0, $i), array_slice($remainingWords, $i + 1));
generateSentences($newPrefix, $newRemainingWords);
}
}
}
generateSentences("", $words);
foreach ($sentences as $sentence) {
echo $sentence . "n";
}
?
```
This code generates all possible permutations of the given words and outputs them as sentences. The order of the words is crucial in the final output, and each word is only used once in each sentence.
To optimize the performance of the current code, we can implement memoization to avoid recomputing the same permutations multiple times. We can create a cache to store the generated permutations and their corresponding sentences. Before generating a new permutation, we can check if it already exists in the cache and use the cached sentence if it does.
Here's an example code snippet with memoization:
```
php
$words = array("world", "amazing", "the");
$sentences = array();
$cache = array();
function generateSentences($prefix, $remainingWords) {
global $sentences, $cache;
$key = implode("-", $remainingWords);
if (isset($cache[$key])) {
foreach ($cache[$key] as $cachedPrefix) {
$sentences[] = $prefix . " " . $cachedPrefix;
}
} else {
if (count($remainingWords) == 0) {
$sentences[] = $prefix;
} else {
$cache[$key] = array();
for ($i = 0; $i < count($remainingWords); $i++) {
$newPrefix = $prefix . " " . $remainingWords[$i];
$newRemainingWords = array_merge(array_slice($remainingWords, 0, $i), array_slice($remainingWords, $i + 1));
generateSentences($newPrefix, $newRemainingWords);
$cache[$key][] = $remainingWords[$i];
}
}
}
}
generateSentences("", $words);
foreach ($sentences as $sentence) {
echo $sentence . "n";
}
?
```
In this code, we create a cache array to store the generated permutations and their corresponding sentences. Before generating a new permutation, we check if it already exists in the cache by using the remaining words as a key. If the key exists, we iterate over the cached prefixes and append them to the current prefix to form a sentence. If the key does not exist, we generate the new permutation as before and add the generated prefixes to the cache. This way, we avoid recomputing the same permutations multiple times and improve the performance of the code.

