```
public static int binarySearch(int[] arr, int x) {
int low = 0;
int high = arr.length - 1;
while (low <= high) {
int mid = (low + high) / 2;
if (arr[mid] == x) {
return mid;
} else if (arr[mid] < x) {
low = mid + 1;
} else {
high = mid - 1;
}
}
return -1;
}
```
Here, `arr` is the sorted array that we want to search for the element `x`. We start by setting the `low` and `high` indices to the beginning and end of the array, respectively. We then enter a while loop that continues until `low` is greater than `high`, meaning that we have searched the entire array and not found the element `x`.
Inside the while loop, we calculate the `mid` index of the array by taking the average of `low` and `high`. We then check if the element at `arr[mid]` is equal to `x`. If it is, we return `mid`, which is the index of the element we were searching for.
If `arr[mid]` is less than `x`, we know that the element we are looking for must be in the right half of the array, so we update `low` to `mid + 1`. If `arr[mid]` is greater than `x`, we know that the element we are looking for must be in the left half of the array, so we update `high` to `mid - 1`.
If we exit the while loop without finding the element `x`, we return `-1` to indicate that the element was not found in the array.
