Inheritance is a fundamental concept in object-oriented programming (OOP) that allows creating new classes from existing ones. In C++, this is achieved using the `class` keyword followed by the parent class name and a colon, followed by the access specifier (`public`, `protected`, or `private`). The derived class inherits all the members of the parent class (i.e., data members and member functions), and it can add new members or override existing ones. For example, consider the following code:

```
class Animal {
public:
void eat() {
cout << "Eating...n";
}
};

class Dog : public Animal { // Dog is a subclass of Animal
public:
void bark() {
cout << "Barking...n";
}
};
```

In this example, the `Dog` class is a subclass of the `Animal` class, and it inherits the `eat()` function. The `Dog` class also adds a new member function `bark()`. Now, we can create an instance of the `Dog` class and call its functions:

```
int main() {
Dog d;
d.eat(); // calls Animal::eat()
d.bark(); // calls Dog::bark()
return 0;
}
```

This will output:

```
Eating...
Barking...
```

In summary, inheritance is a powerful tool that allows creating new classes by reusing existing code and adding new functionality. It also enables polymorphism and is a key feature of OOP.

