class HttpUtils {
public static String sendGet(String url, String parameters, String token) throws Exception {
URL obj = new URL(url + "?" + parameters);
HttpURLConnection con = (HttpURLConnection) obj.openConnection();
con.setRequestMethod("GET");
con.setRequestProperty("Authorization", "Token " + token);
BufferedReader in = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(con.getInputStream()));
String inputLine;
StringBuffer response = new StringBuffer();
while ((inputLine = in.readLine()) != null) {
response.append(inputLine);
}
in.close();
return response.toString();
}
}
class JsonUtils {
public static List parseClimateData(String jsonData) throws Exception {
List climateDataList = new ArrayList<>();
JSONObject jsonObject = new JSONObject(jsonData);
JSONArray jsonArray = jsonObject.getJSONArray("results");
for (int i = 0; i < jsonArray.length(); i++) {
JSONObject resultObject = jsonArray.getJSONObject(i);
long date = resultObject.getLong("date");
double tmax = resultObject.getDouble("TMAX");
double tmin = resultObject.getDouble("TMIN");
double prcp = resultObject.getDouble("PRCP");
ClimateData climateData = new ClimateData(date, tmax, tmin, prcp);
climateDataList.add(climateData);
}
return climateDataList;
}
}
```
In this example, the `ClimateData` class represents a single data point that contains the date, maximum temperature, minimum temperature, and precipitation. The `HttpUtils` class is used to send a GET request to the NOAA CDO API and retrieve the climate data as JSON. The `JsonUtils` class is used to parse the JSON data and create a list of `ClimateData` objects.
The `main` method first retrieves the climate data and then creates a line chart using JFreeChart to visualize the data. Finally, it uses Weka to predict future climate patterns based on the data. The `climate_data.arff` file contains the same data as the JSON response, but in a format that can be read by Weka.
Note that this is just an example, and there are many other machine learning algorithms and libraries that you can use to predict future climate patterns. Additionally, the accuracy of the predictions depends on the quality and quantity of the data.

