How can I implement an algorithm in Scala to generate unique sentences using three words from a list, where each sentence should use one word from each column and should not repeat any of the previously generated sentences? The list of words is given in a table format with three columns and multiple rows.
Here is the Scala code I have written to implement this:
val words = List(
List("word1_col1", "word1_col2", "word1_col3"),
List("word2_col1", "word2_col2", "word2_col3"),
List("word3_col1", "word3_col2", "word3_col3")
)
def generateSentences(numSentences: Int): List[String] = {
var sentences = List[String]()
var usedCombinations = Set[List[String]]()

for(i <- 1 to numSentences) {
var sentence = ""
var newCombination = List[String]()

while(usedCombinations.contains(newCombination)) {
newCombination = List(words(0)(util.Random.nextInt(words(0).size)),
words(1)(util.Random.nextInt(words(1).size)),
words(2)(util.Random.nextInt(words(2).size)))
}

usedCombinations += newCombination
sentence = newCombination(0) + " " + newCombination(1) + " " + newCombination(2)
sentences = sentences :+ sentence
}

return sentences
}
println(generateSentences(10))
How can I further optimize this code to handle large datasets efficiently?

One way to optimize this code is to use a hash set to keep track of used combinations instead of a list. This will make the lookup faster and more efficient, especially with large datasets. Additionally, you can precompute all possible combinations of words and store them in a list or hash set to avoid generating duplicates.
Here is an optimized version of the code:
val words = List(
List("word1_col1", "word1_col2", "word1_col3"),
List("word2_col1", "word2_col2", "word2_col3"),
List("word3_col1", "word3_col2", "word3_col3")
)
val combinations = words(0).flatMap(w1 => words(1).flatMap(w2 => words(2).map(w3 => List(w1, w2, w3))))
def generateSentences(numSentences: Int): List[String] = {
var sentences = List[String]()
var usedCombinations = Set[List[String]]()

while(sentences.length < numSentences && usedCombinations.size < combinations.length) {
val newCombination = combinations(util.Random.nextInt(combinations.length))
if(!usedCombinations.contains(newCombination)) {
usedCombinations += newCombination
val sentence = newCombination.mkString(" ")
sentences = sentences :+ sentence
}
}

return sentences
}
println(generateSentences(10))
In this version, we precompute all possible combinations using the flatMap function, and then use a while loop to generate new sentences until we reach the desired number of sentences or run out of unused combinations. We also use the mkString function to concatenate the words in each combination into a sentence.

