To conduct sentiment analysis using JavaScript and the NLP.js library, you can follow these steps:
1. Install NLP.js library using npm command: `npm install nlp_compromise`
2. Load the library and create a new instance of the `nlp` class:
```
const nlp = require('nlp_compromise');
const nlpInstance = new nlp();
```
3. Use the `nlpInstance` to process the provided text and extract its sentiments:
```
const result = nlpInstance.sentiment(text);
```
4. The `result` object will contain the sentiment score, positive, negative, and neutral percentages. You can access these values as follows:
```
const sentimentScore = result.score;
const positivePercentage = result.positive;
const negativePercentage = result.negative;
const neutralPercentage = result.neutral;
```
5. To extract themes from the text, you can use the `nlpInstance.topics()` method:
```
const themes = nlpInstance.topics(text);
```
6. The `themes` object will contain an array of topics, each with a label and score. You can access the top 3 themes as follows:
```
const topThemes = themes.slice(0, 3).map((theme) => {
return {
label: theme.label,
score: theme.score
}
});
```
7. To exclude irrelevant sentences from the text, you can use the `nlpInstance.sentences()` method to split the text into individual sentences and then filter out the irrelevant ones based on some criteria (e.g., length, keywords, etc.):
```
const sentences = nlpInstance.sentences(text);
const relevantSentences = sentences.filter((sentence) => {
// filter out irrelevant sentences
});
```
8. To gain more profound insights, you can use entity recognition to identify important entities (e.g., people, organizations, locations, etc.) mentioned in the text:
```
const entities = nlpInstance.entities(text);
```
9. The `entities` object will contain an array of entities, each with a label and text. You can access the top 3 entities as follows:
```
const topEntities = entities.slice(0, 3).map((entity) => {
return {
label: entity.label,
text: entity.text
}
});
```
10. Finally, you can output the results in JSON format as follows:
```
const output = {
sentiment: {
score: sentimentScore,
positive: positivePercentage,
