Yes, you can use the Go programming language to generate a PDF file from a LaTeX document. Here is an example code that shows how to do this using the GoTeX package:
```go
package main
import (
"fmt"
"io/ioutil"
"os"
"os/exec"
)
func main() {
// Read the LaTeX file
latex, err := ioutil.ReadFile("harry_potter.tex")
if err != nil {
fmt.Println(err)
return
}
// Run pdflatex to generate the PDF file
cmd := exec.Command("pdflatex", "-output-directory=pdf", "-jobname=harry_potter", "-interaction=batchmode")
cmd.Stdin = bytes.NewReader(latex)
cmd.Stdout = os.Stdout
cmd.Stderr = os.Stderr
err = cmd.Run()
if err != nil {
fmt.Println(err)
return
}
fmt.Println("PDF file generated successfully!")
}
```
This code reads the contents of the LaTeX file "harry_potter.tex", runs pdflatex to generate the PDF file, and saves it in the "pdf" directory with the name "harry_potter.pdf". You can modify the code to suit your needs, such as changing the input file name, output directory, or pdflatex options.

