Certainly! You can use the AVG function in SQL to calculate the average of a sequence of numbers. Here's an example query that would work for your scenario:
```
SELECT AVG(numbers) AS average FROM data;
```
This query selects the average value of the "numbers" column in the "data" table and aliases it as "average". The result will be a single row with a single column containing the average value.
Here's a sample code snippet in SQL that demonstrates how to use this query:
```
-- Connect to the SQL database
$conn = new mysqli($servername, $username, $password, $dbname);
-- Check connection
if ($conn->connect_error) {
die("Connection failed: " . $conn->connect_error);
}
-- Define the SQL query
$sql = "SELECT AVG(numbers) AS average FROM data;";
-- Execute the query and store the result
$result = $conn->query($sql);
-- Check if the query was successful
if ($result->num_rows > 0) {
-- Output the average value
$row = $result->fetch_assoc();
echo "The average value is: " . $row["average"];
} else {
echo "No results found.";
}
-- Close the database connection
$conn->close();
```
This code connects to the SQL database, executes the query, retrieves the result, and outputs the average value. Note that you'll need to replace the `$servername`, `$username`, `$password`, and `$dbname` variables with your own values.

