To implement a dynamic image gallery on a webpage about the Grand Canyon using JavaScript, you can follow the following steps:
1. Create an array of image URLs for the gallery.
2. Create a function to display the gallery images in a modal window.
3. Create a function to handle the click event on the thumbnail images and display the corresponding full-sized image in the modal window.
4. Add buttons to the modal window to allow users to scroll through the other images in the gallery.
To make the gallery responsive and ensure that it loads quickly, you can use lazy loading techniques and optimize the image sizes for web.
Here is a sample JavaScript code snippet to help you achieve this task:
```javascript
// Array of image URLs for the gallery
const images = [
'img1.jpg',
'img2.jpg',
'img3.jpg',
'img4.jpg',
'img5.jpg'
];
// Function to display the gallery images in a modal window
function displayGallery() {
const gallery = document.getElementById('gallery');
gallery.innerHTML = '';
images.forEach((image, index) => {
const img = document.createElement('img');
img.src = image;
img.alt = `Image ${index + 1}`;
img.classList.add('thumbnail');
img.addEventListener('click', () => displayImage(image, index));
gallery.appendChild(img);
});
}
// Function to display the full-sized image in the modal window
function displayImage(image, index) {
const modal = document.getElementById('modal');
const modalImg = document.getElementById('modal-img');
const prevBtn = document.getElementById('prev');
const nextBtn = document.getElementById('next');
modal.style.display = 'block';
modalImg.src = image;
modalImg.alt = `Image ${index + 1}`;
prevBtn.addEventListener('click', () => displayPrevImage(index));
nextBtn.addEventListener('click', () => displayNextImage(index));
}
// Function to handle the click event on the thumbnail images
function displayPrevImage(index) {
const prevIndex = (index === 0) ? images.length - 1 : index - 1;
const prevImage = images[prevIndex];
displayImage(prevImage, prevIndex);
}
function displayNextImage(index) {
const nextIndex = (index === images.length - 1) ? 0 : index + 1;
const nextImage = images[nextIndex];
displayImage(nextImage, nextIndex);
}
// Call the displayGallery function to display the gallery on page load
displayGallery();
```
In this code snippet, we have created an array of image URLs for the gallery and defined three functions to display the gallery, display the full-sized image in the modal window, and handle the click events on the thumbnail images. We have also added buttons to the modal window to allow users to scroll through the other images in the gallery. Finally, we have called the displayGallery function to display the gallery on page load.

