To handle file uploads in PHP, there are several effective techniques that can be used:
1. Use server-side validation to ensure that the file being uploaded is of the correct type and size.
2. Rename the file to prevent overwriting of existing files.
3. Store the file in a secure directory.
Here is an example of how the move_uploaded_file function can be used to save uploaded files securely to the server:
```
if ($_FILES["file"]["error"] == UPLOAD_ERR_OK) {
$tmp_name = $_FILES["file"]["tmp_name"];
$name = basename($_FILES["file"]["name"]);
$extension = pathinfo($name, PATHINFO_EXTENSION);
$new_name = uniqid() . "." . $extension;
$upload_dir = "uploads/";
$allowed_types = array("jpg", "jpeg", "png", "gif");
$max_size = 5000000;
if (in_array($extension, $allowed_types) && $_FILES["file"]["size"] <= $max_size) {
if (!file_exists($upload_dir . $new_name)) {
move_uploaded_file($tmp_name, $upload_dir . $new_name);
echo "File uploaded successfully.";
} else {
echo "File already exists.";
}
} else {
echo "Invalid file type or size.";
}
}
```
This code snippet checks if the file is of an allowed type and size, renames the file to prevent overwriting, and stores the file in the "uploads/" directory. It also checks if the file already exists in the directory.
To resize and manipulate uploaded images to generate thumbnails, we can use the GD library in PHP. Here is an example code snippet:
```
$upload_dir = "uploads/";
$image = $_FILES["file"]["tmp_name"];
$thumbnail_width = 200;
$thumbnail_height = 200;
list($width, $height) = getimagesize($image);
$ratio = $width / $height;
if ($ratio > 1) {
$new_width = $thumbnail_width;
$new_height = $thumbnail_height / $ratio;
} else {
$new_width = $thumbnail_width * $ratio;
$new_height = $thumbnail_height;
}
$thumbnail = imagecreatetruecolor($thumbnail_width, $thumbnail_height);
$image = imagecreatefromjpeg($image);
imagecopyresampled($thumbnail, $image, 0, 0, 0, 0, $new_width, $new_height, $width, $height);
imagejpeg($thumbnail, $upload_dir . "thumbnail_" . $new_name);
```
This code snippet resizes the uploaded image to a specified thumbnail size, creates a new thumbnail image using the GD library, and saves the thumbnail image to the "uploads/" directory with a "thumbnail_" prefix in the file name.

